# CSS Cascade Layer Policy

This project embeds 3rd-party component CSS (PrimeReact 10.x, `@burgantech/pseudo-ui` SDK) alongside Tailwind v4. The CSS cascade must be structured so that these libraries render correctly without manual overrides.

## How the cascade works in this project

Tailwind v4 emits all its output inside native CSS `@layer` blocks:

```
@layer properties   ← lowest priority (layered)
@layer theme
@layer base         ← Tailwind preflight (border:0, margin:0, bg:transparent, …)
@layer components
@layer utilities    ← highest-priority layered CSS
─────────────────
unlayered CSS       ← ALWAYS beats all @layer, regardless of specificity
```

PrimeReact 10.x injects component CSS at runtime via `<style>` tags. These are **unlayered**. Per the CSS cascade specification, unlayered styles always win over layered styles. This means PrimeReact automatically beats Tailwind's preflight — no revert rules, no specificity hacks needed.

## Rules

### R1 — Never use `!important` on global resets

Global resets (`*`, `input`, `button`, `textarea`, `img`, `h1`–`h6`) must **never** carry `!important`. Without `!important`, 3rd-party class-based selectors (`.p-button`, `.p-inputtext`) win on specificity alone. With `!important`, nothing can override them.

```css
/* ✅ correct */
* { box-sizing: border-box; outline: none; }

/* ❌ forbidden */
* { box-sizing: border-box !important; outline: none !important; }
```

### R2 — No Tailwind preflight revert rules inside component hosts

Do not add `revert` rules to undo Tailwind's preflight for 3rd-party components. Tailwind v4 puts preflight in `@layer base`; 3rd-party unlayered CSS already wins. Adding revert rules creates a new specificity competition between the revert and the 3rd-party CSS.

```css
/* ❌ unnecessary and harmful — creates specificity conflict */
.pseudo-ui-host button { background-color: revert; }

/* ✅ not needed — PrimeReact .p-button (unlayered) already beats @layer base */
```

### R3 — App-authored CSS that targets generic elements must use low specificity

If you must style generic HTML elements (not component classes) inside a 3rd-party host zone, use `:where()` to zero the inner selector's specificity. This guarantees the component library's class selectors win on ties.

```css
/* ✅ specificity (0,1,0) — ties with .p-button, PrimeReact wins (injected later) */
.some-host :where(button) { cursor: pointer; }

/* ❌ specificity (0,1,1) — beats .p-button, overrides PrimeReact */
.some-host button { cursor: pointer; }
```

### R4 — Keep `.pseudo-ui-host` CSS minimal

`pseudo-ui-layers.css` must contain **only**:

1. `.pseudo-ui-host` container styles (isolation, font, border, padding, background)
2. `.pseudo-ui-host--fill` / `.pseudo-ui-host__scroll` flex layout
3. Dark-mode tweaks that are genuinely missing from the theme engine

It must **not** contain:
- `--p-*` token definitions (provided by `@primeuix/themes` at runtime)
- `d-*` layout classes (provided by `@burgantech/pseudo-ui/react/style.css`)
- `.p-*` PrimeReact component overrides (provided by PrimeReact runtime CSS)
- Tailwind preflight revert rules (unnecessary per R2)

### R5 — Reserve `!important` for VS Code webview host overrides only

The VS Code webview host injects global styles with `!important` (e.g. on `input`, `textarea`). Fighting those requires `!important` in return. Such rules must be scoped with a comment explaining the VS Code override context and must not be applied globally.

## Quick reference

| CSS source | Cascade level | Priority |
|---|---|---|
| Tailwind v4 preflight | `@layer base` | Lowest |
| Tailwind v4 utilities | `@layer utilities` | Low-medium |
| App global resets (`styles.css`) | Unlayered (no `!important`) | Medium |
| SDK layout CSS (`pseudo-ui/react/style.css`) | Unlayered | Medium |
| PrimeReact runtime CSS (`useStyle`) | Unlayered | Medium (wins ties by injection order) |
| `!important` on any of the above | `!important` layer | Highest — avoid |
